******
[2]
Date: Fri Oct 2012
From: Jennifer MacFarquhar <jennifer.macfarquhar@dhhs.nc.gov> [edited]


Thank you for your phone call and request for clarification. As we discussed this afternoon, _E. coli_ O157 has been isolated from the individuals in question. 2 types of molecular tests, pulse field gel electrophoresis (PFGE), and multi-locus variable tandem repeat analysis (MLVA) have been used to differentiate and identify the particular strain of _E. coli_. The outbreak strain from Cleveland County has a common PFGE pattern, but a unique MLVA pattern. A unique pattern does not imply rarity or enhanced pathogenicity, simply that the strain has not been previously characterized.

--
Jennifer MacFarquhar
Career Epidemiology Field Officer, CDC
Communicable Disease Branch
North Carolina Division of Public Health
Raleigh, NC
<jennifer.macfarquhar@dhhs.nc.gov>

[ProMED-mail thanks Ms MacFarquhar for her prompt reply regarding the nature of the pathogen, clearly a O157:H7 serotype with a unique MLVA pattern.

The state of North Carolina can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at http://healthmap.org/r/3Hk_. Cleveland County can be seen on the map at http://www.digital-topo-maps.com/county-map/north-carolina.shtml. - Mod.LL]

